@rroudt @thunknotes There is another possibility, focused apps and interop.

@rroudt @thunknotes An example. In the early 90s, my company had a programmable outliner called Frontier. It had a rich scripting language and object database. Easy to develop in. People liked the outliner.

cont'd

@rroudt @thunknotes At the time there were two leading page layout and prepress products, Pagemaker and Quark XPress. It turns out there was a strong connection between page layout, scripting and outlining. There was lots you could in the intersection.

@rroudt @thunknotes Instead of PageMaker and Quark doing their own outliner, scripting system, object databases, that were incompatible, instead they created APIs and we wrote glue for them in Frontier, so people had their choice. And other people made outliners and scripting systems.

@rroudt @thunknotes Since these products were often used inside organizations, this meant companies could build their own workflows to take more of the work out of the layout process, and writers could use whatever tools they liked.
